Discrete Time Fourier Analysis
==============================

<table>
	<tr>
		<td></td>
		<td>DT</td>
		<td>CT</td>
	</tr>
	<tr>
		<td>Analysis</td>
		<td>e^{j\omega}=\sum_{-\infty}^{\infty}x[n]e^{-j\omega n}</td>
		<td>e^{j\omega}=\int_{-\infty}^{\infty}x(t)e^{-j\omega t}dt</td>
	</tr>
	<tr>
		<td>Synthesis</td>
		<td>x[n]=\frac{1}{2\pi} \int_{2\pi} X[e^{j\omega}]e^{j\omega n}d\omega</td>
		<td>x(t)=\frac{1}{2\pi} \int_{-\infty}^{\infty} X[e^{j\omega}]e^{j\omega t}d\omega</td>
	</tr>
</table>

Discrete time only has to satisfy Dirichlet condition #1, that is, the signal is absolutely summable.
